\title{Information Dimension Reduction of Time-Evolving Densities}
\maketitle

Dimension is a quantity defined for measures, and it is only useful when the measure is singular, because absolutely continuous measures always have dimension equal to the dimension of the space. For this reason, applications of dimension theory to dynamical systems have always focused on the dimension of the attractor when the system admits a unique invariant measure.

The formula thus far has been 1) evolve the system for infinite time, 2) calculate a dimension for the invariant measure or make approximations otherwise. The first problem with this approach is that the infinite time limit of the measure may not exist, which forces us to do things like restrict analysis to ergodic theory and use dimension approximations like Kaplan-Yorke dimension. While this already complicates things significantly, the bigger problem is that there is no explanation for what happens to dimension in between finite-time evolution and the infinite time limit. Dimension instantaneously collapses from the ambient dimension to the attractor dimension when transitioning between finite and infinite time. In this picture, dimension has no physical meaning because any reduction of entropy can't be attributed to any physical process!

In this very rough manuscript, I derive a definition for dimension which gives it a physically meaningful time evolution equation. I define information dimension entirely in terms of a smooth measure evolving under the Liouville equation by analyzing its finite-time asymptotic behavior.

\section{Dynamical Setting}

\noindent Consider the general nonlinear autonomous ODE:

\[
\frac{\mathrm d}{\mathrm dt} x(t) = f(x(t)), \qquad x(0) = x_0 \in \mathbb{R}^n
\]

\noindent Assume it has a unique solution, and therefore a semi-flow \(\Phi_t: \mathbb{R}^n \mapsto \mathbb{R}^n\) exists such that \(x(t) = \Phi_t(x_0)\). For a probability distribution over initial conditions we define a density \(\rho(x,t)\) and we can write its evolution under the flow generated by the ODE with a continuity (Liouville) equation:

\[
\partial_t \rho(x,t) = \mathcal{L}_f \rho(x,t) = -\nabla \cdot \left( f(x)\, \rho(x,t) \right), \qquad \rho(x,0) = \rho_0(x) \in C^\infty(\mathbb{R}^n)
\]

\noindent where \(\mathcal{L}_f\) is the Liouville operator which we'll use as shorthand for this equation. The equation has the solution:

\[
\rho(x,t) = e^{t \mathcal{L}_f} \rho_0(x)
\]

\section{Definition of Information Dimension}

The standard definition of information dimension of a measure requires you to partition \(\mathbb{R}^n\) into \(\varepsilon^{-n}\) discrete points \(x_i\) and integrate the measure over the \(\varepsilon\)-diameter ball \(B_\varepsilon(x_i)\) around each point. If the limit exists, the information dimension is defined as follows:

\begin{align*}
H_\varepsilon[\mu] &= -\sum_i \mu(B_\varepsilon(x_i)) \log \mu(B_\varepsilon(x_i)) \\
\mathcal{D}_I[\mu] &= \lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \frac{H_\varepsilon[\mu]}{\log(1/\varepsilon)}
\end{align*}

\noindent This definition is not very insightful for measures that evolve over time because the partition is rigid and can't be linked to the dynamics into a meaningful way. We will instead focus on an equivalent but lesser known definition which simply uses a gaussian kernel to coarse-grain the measure:

\begin{align*}
g_\sigma(x) &= \frac{1}{(\sqrt{2\pi} \sigma)^{d}}\exp\left(-\frac{\|x\|^{2}}{2\sigma^2}\right) \\[8pt]
\rho_\sigma(x) &= (\mu * g_\sigma)(x) = \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} g_\sigma(x-y) \mu(dy) \\[8pt]
\mathcal{D}_I[\mu] &= n + \lim_{\sigma \downarrow 0} \frac{h[\rho_\sigma]}{\log(1/\sigma)}
\end{align*}


\noindent with \(h[\rho]=-\int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \rho(x) \log \rho(x) \mathrm{d}x \), the differential entropy functional. In this form, we need not define a rigid partition, which grants of differentiability w.r.t. \(\sigma\). In fact, the convolutional definition can already be expressed as the small-\(\sigma\) limit of a logarithmic derivative:

\[
\mathcal{D}_I = n - \lim_{\sigma \downarrow 0} \frac{d h[\rho_\sigma]}{d \log \sigma} = n - \lim_{\sigma \downarrow 0} \sigma \partial_\sigma h[\rho_\sigma]
\]

\noindent The local dimension \(d_I(x)\), whose expectation under \(\mu\) is \(\mathcal{D}_I\), admits a similar definition in terms of a derivative:

\begin{align*}
d_I(x)   &= n + \lim_{\sigma \downarrow 0} \sigma \partial_\sigma \log \rho_\sigma(x) \\
\mathcal{D}_I &= \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} d_I(x)\, \mu(\mathrm{d}x)
\end{align*}

\noindent Recall that the solution to the heat equation \(\partial_t u = \Delta u\) is identical to convolving a gaussian with width \(\sigma = \sqrt{2t}\). Therefore, a gaussian convolution \((\,\cdot * g_\sigma)\) can be written using the operator exponential \(e^{\frac{1}{2}\sigma^2 \Delta}\). Labelling \(\varepsilon = \tfrac{1}{2}\sigma^2\) and using \(\partial_\sigma = \sigma \partial_\varepsilon\), we get:

\begin{align*}
d_I[\mu](x) &= n + 2\lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \varepsilon \partial_\varepsilon \log(e^{\varepsilon \Delta}\mu)(x) \\
            &= n + 2\lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \varepsilon \frac{\Delta \rho_\varepsilon(x)}{\rho_\varepsilon(x)} \\
            &= n + 2\lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \varepsilon \left(\Delta \log \rho_\varepsilon + \|\nabla \log \rho_\varepsilon\|^2\right)
\end{align*}

\noindent where I have somewhat confusingly redefined \(\rho_\varepsilon = (\rho_\sigma)_{\sigma=\sqrt{2 \varepsilon}}\). This will be the notation going forward for the measure coarse-grained by the heat semigroup.

\section{Finite Time Information Content}

Up until now we have simply been rearranging existing definitions for the global and local information dimension, but this final expression which at we have arrived is going to be exactly what we need to analyze time-evolving measures. Specifically, we'll be able to derive how smooth n-dimensional initial measures concentrate onto lower-dimensional attractors by looking at the rate of change of the local information dimension over finite time horizons.

If we do this naively, and simply try to take the time derivative of the local information dimension for a measure evolving under the Liouville equation, we find that the time derivative is always zero. This is because in finite time, the measure remains smooth and therefore the dimension truly does not change. However, if we try to first take the \(t\!\to\!\infty\) limit of the measure and then calculate the local information dimension or its time derivative, we are unable to take the limit because the limit measure may not actually exist. Even if it does (e.g. when the system admits an SRB measure), the rate of change will once again be zero because the measure has already concentrated onto the attractor and is no longer evolving. What I aim to do is find a continuous path from \(t = 0\) to the \(t\!\to\!\infty\) that lets us track how the information dimension changes over time. Specifically, I will derive a physically meaningful rate of change of the global \& local information dimension that singles out one information-geometric quantity as the source of dimension loss. We will begin by defining the finite-time, coarse-grain information content of a probability density whose evolution is governed by the drift \(f\) as follows:

\[
\mathrm{j}_f(x(t),t,\varepsilon) = n + 2\log\frac{\rho_\varepsilon(x(t),t)}{\rho_0(x(0))}
\]

\noindent The derivative w.r.t. \(\varepsilon\) is:
\begin{align*}
\partial_\varepsilon \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon) &= 2 \partial_{\varepsilon} \log \rho_\varepsilon(x,t) \\
&= 2 \left(\Delta \log \rho_\varepsilon + \|\nabla \log \rho_\varepsilon\|^2\right)
\end{align*}

\noindent which is reminiscent of the information dimension definition. Plugging in \(\varepsilon = 0\) recovers a familiar identity from the Liouville equation relating log density change along a trajectory to phase space contraction:
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{j}_f(x(t),t,0) &= n + 2 \log \frac{\rho(x(t),t)}{\rho_0(x(0))} \\
&= n - 2 \int_0^t \nabla \cdot f(x(\tau)) \, \mathrm{d}\tau \\
&=\vcentcolon n - 2 \Lambda(x_0,t)
\end{align*}
\noindent In this expression, \(\Lambda(x_0,t)\) is the integral of the sum of the eigenvalues \(\nabla f\) and equivalently \(t\) times the sum of all finite time Lyapunov exponents. For volume preserving flows (e.g. Hamiltonian), \(\Lambda = 0\) so as expected the dimension does not change without coarse-graining.

We can also define the global information content \(\mathcal{J}_f(t,\varepsilon)\) as the expectation of \(\mathrm{j}_f\) over the time-evolved measure \(\rho(x,t)\):
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{J}_f(t,\varepsilon) &= \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \mathrm{j}_f(x(t),t,\varepsilon) \, \rho(x,t) \, \mathrm{d}x \\[8pt]
&= n + 2 \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \log \left( \frac{\rho_\varepsilon(x(t),t)}{\rho_0(x(0))}\right) \, \rho(x,t) \, \mathrm{d}x \\[8pt]
&= n + 2 \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \log \left( \frac{\rho_\varepsilon(x(t),t)}{\rho(x(t),t)}\right) \, \rho(x,t) \, \mathrm{d}x + 2\int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \log \left( \frac{\rho(x(t),t)}{\rho_0(x(0))}\right) \, \rho(x,t) \, \mathrm{d}x \\[8pt]
&=\vcentcolon n - 2 D_\text{KL}\left[\,\rho(\cdot,t) \,\|\, \rho_\varepsilon(\cdot,t)\,\right] - 2 \bar \Lambda(t)
\end{align*}
Here, \(D_\text{KL}\) is the Kullback-Leibler divergence between the time-evolved measure and the coarse-grained measure, and \(\bar \Lambda(t)\) is the expectation of \(\Lambda(x_0,t)\) over the time-evolved measure.

We can now plug in these definitions for local and global information content in  The local information dimension can therefore be interpreted as the small \(\varepsilon\) limit of the information content.
\begin{align*}
d_I(x,T) &= \lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \lim_{t \to T} n + \varepsilon \partial_\varepsilon \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon)\\
&= \lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \lim_{t \to T} n + \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,0) - \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon) + \mathcal{O}(\varepsilon^2)\\
&= \lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \lim_{t \to T} \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon) + 2 \Lambda(x_0,t)
\end{align*}

\noindent Similarly, the expectation of \(\mathrm{j}_f\) over the time-evolved measure is a KL divergence and its \(\varepsilon \to 0\) limit gives the global information dimension:
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{D}_I(T) &= \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \lim_{t \to T} \left(\mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon) + 2 \Lambda(x(0),t)\right) \, \rho(x,t) \, \mathrm{d}x \\[8pt]
&= \lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \lim_{t \to T} \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \left(\mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon) + 2 \Lambda(x(0),t)\right) \, \rho(x,t) \, \mathrm{d}x \\[8pt]
&= \lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \lim_{t \to T} \left(n - 2 D_\text{KL}\left[\,\rho(\cdot,t) \,\|\, \rho_\varepsilon(\cdot,t)\,\right] - 2 \bar\Lambda(t) + 2\bar \Lambda(t) \right) \\[8pt]
&= n - 2\lim_{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \lim_{t \to T} D_\text{KL}\left[\,\rho(\cdot,t) \,\|\, \rho_\varepsilon(\cdot,t)\,\right] \\
\end{align*}
\noindent For any finite time, we find that the dimensions all coincide \(d_I(x,t) = \mathcal{D}_I(t) = n = d_I[\mu_t](x) = \mathcal{D}_I[\mu_t]\). If we evaluate the limit as \(t \to \infty\) (this must be done inside the \(\varepsilon \to 0\) limit), we once again find \(d_I(x,\infty) = d_I[\mu_\infty](x)\) and \(\mathcal{D}_I(\infty) = \mathcal{D}_I[\mu_\infty]\) when \(\mu_\infty\) exists because the limits were defined to be exactly equivalent to the definitions of the local and global information dimension. 

With this generalized definition in terms of the information content \(\mathrm{j}_f\), we can now ask the question: can we modify the definition of dimension of so it exactly matches the information dimension at \(t=0\) and \(t\to\infty\) while being perfectly continuous in between? The answer is yes, by replacing the \(\varepsilon \to 0\) limit with a joint limit via a carefully chosen relation \(\varepsilon = \varepsilon(t)\). I will show that there is a unique relation \(\varepsilon = \varepsilon(t)\) which keeps the rate of change of the information content finite and non-zero, generating a continuous path from \(\mathcal{D}_I(0)\) to \(\mathcal{D}_I(\infty)\).

\section{Time Evolution of Information Content}

\noindent Let's calculate the rate of change of the information content prior to taking any limits. Let \(s = \nabla \log \rho_\varepsilon(x,t)\), which is typically called the score. The information content, expanded to first order in \(\varepsilon\), is:
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon) &= \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,0 ) + \varepsilon \partial_\varepsilon \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon) + \mathcal{O}(\varepsilon^2) \\
&= n + 2\,\varepsilon \left( \Delta \log \rho_\varepsilon(x,t) + \|\nabla \log \rho_\varepsilon(x,t)\|^2 \right) - 2 \Lambda(x_0,t) + \mathcal{O}(\varepsilon^2) \\
&= n + 2\,\varepsilon\,( \nabla \cdot s + \|s\|^2) - 2 \Lambda(x_0,t) + \mathcal{O}(\varepsilon^2)
\end{align*}
Below we calculate the time derivatives \(\partial_t s\), \(\partial_t \nabla \cdot s\) and \(\partial_t \|s\|^2\).

\begin{align*}
\partial_t s &= \partial_t \nabla \log \rho_\varepsilon(x,t) \\
&= \partial_t \nabla \log e^{\varepsilon \Delta}e^{t \mathcal{L}_f}\rho_0(x) \\
&= \nabla \frac{e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mathcal{L}_f e^{t \mathcal{L}_f}\rho_0(x)}{e^{\varepsilon \Delta}e^{t \mathcal{L}_f}\rho_0(x)} \\
&= \nabla \left(\frac{\mathcal{L}_f e^{\varepsilon \Delta}e^{t \mathcal{L}_f}\rho_0(x)}{e^{\varepsilon \Delta}e^{t \mathcal{L}_f}\rho_0(x)} + \frac{[e^{\varepsilon \Delta}, \mathcal{L}_f] e^{t \mathcal{L}_f}\rho_0(x)}{e^{\varepsilon \Delta}e^{t \mathcal{L}_f}\rho_0(x)}\right) \\
&= \nabla \left(\frac{-\nabla \cdot (f(x)\, \rho_\varepsilon(x,t))}{\rho_\varepsilon(x,t)} + \mathcal{O}( \varepsilon e^{\lambda t})\right) \\
&= \nabla \left(-\nabla \cdot f - f \cdot s \right) + \mathcal{O}( \varepsilon e^{\lambda t})\\
&= -\underbrace{\nabla (\nabla \cdot f)}_{\mathcal{O}(1)}
- \underbrace{\nabla f^\top s}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{\lambda t})}
- \underbrace{(\nabla s) f}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{\lambda t})}
+\, \mathcal{O}( \varepsilon e^{\lambda t}) \\
%
\partial_t \nabla \cdot s &= \nabla \cdot \partial_t s \\
&= \nabla \cdot \left(-\nabla (\nabla \cdot f) - \nabla f^\top s  - (\nabla s) f + \mathcal{O}( \varepsilon e^{\lambda t})\right) \\
&= -\underbrace{\Delta (\nabla \cdot f)}_{\mathcal{O}(1)}
- \underbrace{(\Delta f)\,s}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{\lambda t})}
- \underbrace{\nabla f \!:\! \nabla s}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{\lambda t})}
+\, \mathcal{O}( \varepsilon e^{\lambda t})\\
%
\partial_t \|s\|^2 &= 2 s \cdot \partial_t s \\
&= 2 s \cdot \left(-\nabla (\nabla \cdot f) - \nabla f^\top s  - (\nabla s) f + \mathcal{O}( \varepsilon e^{\lambda t})\right) \\
&= -\underbrace{2 s \cdot \nabla (\nabla \cdot f)}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{\lambda t})}
- \underbrace{2 s^\top \nabla f^\top s}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{2\lambda t})}
- \underbrace{2 s^\top (\nabla s) f}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{2\lambda t})}
+\, \mathcal{O}( \varepsilon e^{\lambda t}) \\
%
\partial_t \mathrm{j}_f &= 2 \,\varepsilon\, \partial_t \left(\nabla \cdot s + \|s\|^2\right) - 2\partial_t \Lambda(x_0,t) + \,\mathcal{O}(\varepsilon^2) \\
&= 2 \underbrace{\varepsilon\, \partial_t \left(\nabla \cdot s\right)}_{\mathcal{O}(\varepsilon e^{\lambda t})} + 2 \underbrace{\varepsilon\, \partial_t \|s\|^2}_{\mathcal{O}(\varepsilon e^{2\lambda t})} - 2 \underbrace{\nabla \cdot f}_{\mathcal{O}(1)} + \,\mathcal{O}(\varepsilon^2)\\
\end{align*}

\noindent For the material derivative defined as \(\frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} = \partial_t + f \cdot \nabla\), the \((\nabla s) f\) terms cancel out, so we get:

\begin{align*}
\frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} s &= -\underbrace{\nabla (\nabla \cdot f)}_{\mathcal{O}(1)}
- \underbrace{\nabla f^\top s}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{\lambda t})}
+\,\mathcal{O}( \varepsilon e^{\lambda t}) \\
\frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} \nabla \cdot s &= -\underbrace{\Delta (\nabla \cdot f)}_{\mathcal{O}(1)}
- \underbrace{(\Delta f)\,s}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{\lambda t})}
- \underbrace{\nabla f \!:\! \nabla s}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{\lambda t})}
+\,\mathcal{O}( \varepsilon e^{\lambda t})\\
\frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} \|s\|^2 &= -2\underbrace{s \cdot \nabla (\nabla \cdot f)}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{\lambda t})}
- 2\underbrace{s^\top \nabla f^\top s}_{\mathcal{O}(e^{2\lambda t})}
+\,\mathcal{O}(\varepsilon e^{\lambda t})\\
\frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} \mathrm{j}_f &= 2\underbrace{\varepsilon \frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} \nabla \cdot s}_{\varepsilon e^{\lambda t}} 
+ 2\underbrace{\varepsilon \frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} \|s\|^2}_{\varepsilon e^{2\lambda t}} - 2 \underbrace{\nabla \cdot f}_{\mathcal{O}(1)} + \,\mathcal{O}(\varepsilon^2)\\
\end{align*}


\noindent An equivalent way to arrive at the above expression is to directly evaluate \(\partial_t \mathrm{j}_f\). One would then find that \(\frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} \mathrm{j}_f = [e^{\varepsilon \Delta}, \mathcal{L}_f] \rho / \rho_\varepsilon\), and to first order in \(\varepsilon\), \(\frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} \mathrm{j}_f = \varepsilon [\Delta, \mathcal{L}_f] \rho / \rho_\varepsilon\) which contains the exact same terms as above. 

By carefully keeping track of the order of the terms, we find that there is a unique relation \(t=t(\varepsilon)\) such that \(\frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt}\mathrm{j}_f\) is neither always zero nor divergent as \(\varepsilon \to 0\). The highest order term is of order \(\mathcal{O}(\varepsilon e^{2\lambda t})\), so
the relation has to be \(\varepsilon(t) = \varepsilon_0 e^{-2\lambda t}\), or equivalently \(t(\varepsilon) = -\frac{\log \varepsilon / \varepsilon_0}{2\lambda} \). The initial coarse-graining scale \(\varepsilon_0\) has a unique value which must be chosen to satisfy the initial condition \(\mathrm{j}_f(x,0,\varepsilon_0) = n\). 

\begin{align*}
\frac{\mathrm d}{\mathrm dt} \mathrm{j}_f(x(t), t, \varepsilon(t)) &= \frac{\mathrm D}{\mathrm Dt} \mathrm{j}_f(x(t), t, \varepsilon(t)) + \dot\varepsilon(t)\, \partial_\varepsilon \mathrm{j}_f(x(t), t, \varepsilon(t)) \\
&= -4\,\varepsilon(t) \bigl(s^\top \nabla f^\top s \bigr) - 2\nabla \cdot f - 4 \lambda\varepsilon(t) \left(\nabla \cdot s + \|s\|^2\right) \\
&= -2\nabla \cdot f -4\, \varepsilon_0\, e^{-2\lambda t} \left(s^\top \nabla f^\top s + \lambda \nabla \cdot s + \lambda \|s\|^2\right)
\end{align*}

\noindent Integrating this quantity, we get an expression for the information content at time \(t\):

\begin{align*}
\mathrm{j}_f(x(t), t, \varepsilon(t)) 
&= \mathrm{j}_f(x_0, 0, \varepsilon_0) - 2\Lambda(x_0,t) \\
&\quad - 2\,\varepsilon_0 \int_0^t e^{-2\lambda \tau} \left(s^\top \nabla f^\top s + \lambda \nabla \cdot s + \lambda \|s\|^2\right) d\tau
\end{align*}

\noindent The global information is the expectation of that:

\begin{align*}
\mathcal{J}_f(t) &= \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \mathrm{j}_f\bigl(x(t), t, \varepsilon(t)\bigr) \, \rho (x,t) \, \mathrm{d}x \\
&= n - 2\bar\Lambda(t) - 2\,\varepsilon_0 \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \! \int_0^t  e^{-2\lambda \tau} \left(s^\top \nabla f^\top s + \lambda \nabla \cdot s + \lambda \|s\|^2\right) \, d\tau \, \rho(x,t)\, \mathrm{d}x
\end{align*}

\noindent Here I use the shorthand \(s = \nabla \log \rho_{\varepsilon(\tau)}(x,\tau)\) which is the score of the coarse-grained density evaluated at the integration time \(\tau\). What we've done is select a smoothing schedule that guarantees the infinite time limit of the information content is finite and not trivially zero. It can, of course, oscillate indefinitely but in that case we can analyze the superior/inferior limits or its time average.

\section{Asymptotic Convergence to Information Dimension}
We already know that at \(t=0\), the information content is equal to the ambient dimension \(\mathrm{j}_f(x,0,\varepsilon_0) = n\). I now show that the information content at \(t\to\infty\) is equal to the information dimension of the invariant measure when the system admits a unique invariant measure. Specifically, the following statements hold when the double limits exist:

\begin{align*}
d_I[\mu_{\infty}](x) &= \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0}\lim_{t \to \infty} \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon) + 2\Lambda(x_0,t) = \lim_{t \to \infty} \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon(t)) + 2\Lambda(x_0,t) \\[8pt]
\mathcal{D}_I[\mu_{\infty}] &= \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0}\lim_{t \to \infty} \mathcal{J}_f(t, \varepsilon) + 2\Lambda(x_0,t) = \lim_{t \to \infty} \mathcal{J}_f(t, \varepsilon(t)) + 2\Lambda(x_0,t)
\end{align*}

\noindent \textit{Proof:} Let's denote the error between the information content and the information dimension by \(\eta\):

\begin{align*}
\eta(x) &= \left\| \left(\lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \lim_{t \to \infty} \mathrm{j}_f(x, t, \varepsilon) + 2\Lambda(x_0, t)\right) - \lim_{t \to \infty} \left(\mathrm{j}_f(x, t, \varepsilon(t)) + 2\Lambda(x_0, t)\right) \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&= \left\| \left(\lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \lim_{t \to \infty} \mathrm{j}_f(x, t, \varepsilon)\right) - \lim_{t \to \infty} \mathrm{j}_f(x, t, \varepsilon(t)) \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&= \left\| \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \lim_{t \to \infty} \left[\mathrm{j}_f(x, t, \varepsilon)\right] - \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \left[\mathrm{j}_f(x, t(\varepsilon), \varepsilon)\right] \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&= \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \left\| \left(\lim_{t \to \infty} n + \log \frac{e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\rho(x,t)}{\rho_0(x_0)} \right) - n - \log \frac{e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\rho(x,t(\varepsilon))}{\rho_0(x_0)} \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&= \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \left\| \log \left( \lim_{t \to \infty} e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\rho(x,t)\right)  - \log \left( e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\rho(x,t(\varepsilon)) \right) \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&= \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \left\| \log \left( e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\mu_\infty\right)(x)  - \log \left( e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\mu_{t(\varepsilon)} \right) \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&=\vcentcolon \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \eta(x,\varepsilon)
\end{align*}
\noindent Using a generalization of the identity \(|\log(a) - \log(b)| \le \frac{|a-b|}{\min(a,b)}\) for \(a,b > 0\), we can bound the error \(\eta(x,\varepsilon)\):

\begin{align*}
\eta(x,\varepsilon) &= \left\| \log \left( e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\mu_\infty\right)(x)  - \log \left( e^{\varepsilon \Delta }\mu_{t(\varepsilon)} \right) \right\|_{L^\infty} \\
&\le \frac{\big\| e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_{t(\varepsilon)} - e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty \big\|_{L^\infty}}{\underset{x}{\operatorname{ess\, inf}} \left(e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_{t(\varepsilon)}(x) \wedge e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty(x)\right)} \\
\end{align*}
\noindent A known result when an invariant measure exists is:

\[
\big\| e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_{t} - e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty \big\|_{L^\infty} \le \big\|\mu_{t} - \mu_\infty \big\|_{TV} \le C e^{-\lambda^* t}
\]

\noindent From the existence of the local dimension \(d_I[\mu_\infty](x)\), we know that:

\[
(e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty)(x) \ge c(x)\, \varepsilon^{\frac{d_I(x) - n}{2}} \ge c^* \, \varepsilon^{\frac{d^* - n}{2}} \qquad \forall x \in \mathbb{R}^n
\]

\noindent where \(c^* = c(x^*), d^* = d_I(x^*)\) and \(x^* = \operatorname{arg\,min}_x d_I(x)\). Using the asymptotic closeness of the two smoothed measures, we can show that the wedge is bounded:

\begin{align*}
e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_{t(\varepsilon)} \wedge e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty 
&\ge c^* \, \varepsilon^{\frac{d^* - n}{2}} - \|e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_{t(\varepsilon)} - e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty\|_{L^\infty} \\
&\ge c^* \, \varepsilon^{\frac{d^* - n}{2}} - C e^{-\lambda^* t(\varepsilon)}\\
&\ge c^* \, \varepsilon^{\frac{d^* - n}{2}} - C (\tfrac{\varepsilon}{\varepsilon_0})^{\frac{\lambda^*}{2\lambda}} \\
&\ge \frac{c^*}{2} \, \varepsilon^{\frac{d^* - n}{2}}
\end{align*}

\noindent Here we absorb the second term into the constant because there will always exist a \(\varepsilon\) such that the first term less than half the second term since \(\lambda^*/2\lambda > 0\). Now we can plug in these bounds into the error:

\begin{align*}
\eta(x,\varepsilon)& \le \frac{\big\| e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_{t(\varepsilon)} - e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty \big\|_{L^\infty}}{\underset{x}{\operatorname{ess\, inf}} \left(e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_{t(\varepsilon)}(x) \wedge e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \mu_\infty(x)\right)} \\[8pt]
&\le 2\frac{C e^{-\lambda^* t(\varepsilon)}}{c^* \, \varepsilon^{\frac{d^* - n}{2}}} \\[8pt]
&= \frac{C (\tfrac{\varepsilon}{\varepsilon_0})^{\frac{\lambda^*}{2\lambda}}}{c^* \, \varepsilon^{\frac{d^* - n}{2}}} \\[8pt]
&= \mathcal{O}(\varepsilon^\alpha) \\
\end{align*}
\noindent with \(\alpha = \frac{\lambda^*}{2\lambda} - \frac{d^* - n}{2} > 0\). Finally, plugging this into the limit, we find that:

\[
\lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \eta(x,\varepsilon) = \lim_{\varepsilon \to 0} \mathcal{O}(\varepsilon^\alpha) = 0
\]

\noindent implying that \(\lim_{t\to \infty} \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon(t)) = d_I[\mu_\infty](x)\). Taking the expectation of the local information dimension shows that the same equality holds for global information dimension. \(\square\)

\section{Physical Information}

Motivated by the result in the previous section, I define the quantities called local and global \textit{physical information}, respectively:

\begin{align*}
\mathrm{i}_f(x,t) &\vcentcolon= \mathrm{j}_f(x,t,\varepsilon(t)) + 2\Lambda(x_0,t) \\
&= n + 2\log\frac{e^{\varepsilon(t) \Delta} \rho(x,t)}{\rho(x,t)}\\[10pt]
\mathcal{I}_f(t) &\vcentcolon= \mathcal{J}_f(t,\varepsilon(t)) + 2\bar\Lambda(t) \\
&= n + 2\int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \log\frac{e^{\varepsilon(t) \Delta} \rho(x,t)}{\rho(x,t)} \, \rho(x,t)\, \mathrm{d}x
\end{align*}

\noindent where \(\varepsilon(t) = -\varepsilon_0 e^{-\lambda t}\). The time derivatives of these quantities are:
\begin{align*}
\frac{\mathrm d}{\mathrm dt} \mathrm{i}_f(x,t) &= 2\,\varepsilon(t) \left(s_{\varepsilon(t)}^\top \nabla f^\top s_{\varepsilon(t)} + \lambda \nabla \cdot s_{\varepsilon(t)} + \lambda \|s_{\varepsilon(t)}\|^2\right) \\[8pt]
\frac{\mathrm d}{\mathrm dt} \mathcal{I}_f(t) &= 2\,\varepsilon(t) \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} \left(s_{\varepsilon(t)}^\top \nabla f^\top s_{\varepsilon(t)} + \lambda \nabla \cdot s_{\varepsilon(t)} + \lambda \|s_{\varepsilon(t)}\|^2\right) \rho(x,t)\, \mathrm{d}x
\end{align*}
\noindent where \(s_\varepsilon = \nabla \log e^{\varepsilon \Delta} \rho(x,t)\) denotes the score of the \(\varepsilon\)-smoothed dynamically evolved density. Both quantities share the important property that they are equal to the information dimension of a dynamically evolved measure at \(t=0\) and \(t\to\infty\):
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{i}_f(x,0) &= d_I[\mu](x) = n, &\lim_{t \to \infty}\mathrm{i}_f(x,t) &= \lim_{t \to \infty} d_I[e^{t \mathcal{L}_f}\mu](x) \\[8pt]
\mathcal{I}_f(0) &= \mathcal{D}_I[\mu] = n, &\lim_{t \to \infty}\mathcal{I}_f(t) &= \lim_{t \to \infty} \mathcal{D}_I[e^{t \mathcal{L}_f}\mu]
\end{align*}

